{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> νόσος</b>, <br /> <i>Epic dialect</i> and <i>Ionic dialect</i> (not <i>Doric dialect</i>,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare “Berl.Sitzb.” 1927.156 (from Cyrene))\">Refs</a>] <b>νοῦσος</b>, ἡ, <b>sickness, disease, plague,</b> νοῦσον ἀνὰ στρατὸν ὦρσε κακήν (i.e. Apollo), ὀλέκοντο δὲ λαοί [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.10; νοῦσόν γ᾽ οὔ πως ἔστι Διὸς μεγάλου ἀλέασθαι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.411; δολιχὴ ν. 11.172; νοῦσοι ἀργαλέαι 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 92:— Phrases: ἐς ν. πεσεῖν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 473; ἐς ν. ἐμπίπτειν 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 1.20; νόσον ἐμπεπτωκέναι τοῖς κτήνεσιν 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 8.3.41; μοι ν. ἐπήλυθεν 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.200; νόσῳ ληφθέντι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 445 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κάμνειν νόσον, ὑπὸ νόσου, see at {κάμν; ἀσθενεῖν ταύτην τὴν νόσον} [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 19.24; ἐκ τῆς νούσου ἀνέστη 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.22 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; θήλεα ν.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 105, compare 2nd c.AD: Herodianus Grammaticus 4.12.2; ἱερὰ νόσος, see at {ἱερός} IV. 8: ν. defined, 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 7.43. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> generally, <b>distress, anguish,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 527, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 544 (Lyric poetry), etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>disease of mind,</b> especially caused by madness, passion, vice, etc., ν. φρενῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 750 (troch.)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; θεία ν., i.e. <b>madness,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.B